  "prompt": "How do you choose an unresponsive yoyo?",
  "response": "Choosing an unresponsive yoyo can seem daunting, but it's a rewarding experience once you understand the key aspects. Here's a breakdown of what to consider:\n\n**1. Shape & Profile:**\n\n*   **Butterfly (Wing) Shape:** The most common and versatile shape. Wide gap allows for easier string tricks. Good for beginners transitioning to unresponsive.\n*   **O-Shape/Round:** More traditional and often more comfortable in the hand. Can be more stable, but the narrower gap can make string tricks slightly harder.\n*   **H-Shape:** A variation on the butterfly shape with more pronounced \"humps\" on the sides. Often offers good stability and spin time.\n*   **V-Shape:** Aggressive shape, known for speed and stability. Can be less forgiving for beginners.\n\n**Recommendation:** Start with a Butterfly or H-Shape for a good balance of versatility and stability.\n\n**2. Material:**\n\n*   **Aluminum:** The most common material for unresponsive yoyos. Durable, offers good weight distribution, and affordable. Various aluminum alloys (6061, 7075) exist, with 7075 being generally lighter and stronger, hence more expensive.\n*   **Delrin (Plastic):**  A great option for budget-friendly unresponsive yoyos.  Delrin is durable and offers a different feel than aluminum (often softer/smoother).  Can be a good choice for learning tricks without damaging your expensive yoyo.\n*   **Titanium:** The most expensive material. Very lightweight and extremely durable. Offers unique performance characteristics prized by experienced players.\n*   **Bi-Metal:**  Combines aluminum with another metal (often stainless steel) concentrated on the rims.  This maximizes weight distribution, leading to longer spin times and increased stability. Bi-metals tend to be more expensive.\n\n**Recommendation:** Aluminum (6061 or 7075) is a great starting point. Delrin is a good budget option. Save Bi-Metal and Titanium for when you're more experienced.\n\n**3. Weight:**\n\n*   **Heavier Yoyos (66g+):**  More stable and can spin longer.  Better for slower, more controlled tricks and for players who prefer a solid, substantial feel.\n*   **Lighter Yoyos (60g-65g):**  Faster and more agile in play.  Good for fast, complex tricks.\n*   **Medium Weight (63g-66g):**  A good compromise between stability and agility. Ideal for a well-rounded player.\n\n**Recommendation:** Start with a weight in the 64g-67g range. This offers a good balance.\n\n**4. Diameter & Width:**\n\n*   **Diameter:** The overall size of the yoyo. Most unresponsive yoyos are in the 50-58mm range. Smaller diameters can feel more compact and nimble, while larger diameters can feel more stable.\n*   **Width:** The distance between the two halves of the yoyo. A wider gap generally makes string tricks easier because it provides more room for string layers. Narrower gaps can be more stable.\n\n**Recommendation:**  Look for a diameter around 54-57mm and a width of 42-47mm as a good starting point.\n\n**5. Bearing & Response System:**\n\n*   **Bearing:** The bearing is crucial for spin time. Look for a \"Size C\" bearing (the most common size).\n    *   **Stainless Steel Bearings:** Durable and long-lasting. A good general choice.\n    *   **Ceramic Bearings:** More expensive, offer less friction and potentially longer spin times. Often require more maintenance.\n    *   **Concave/CenterTrac Bearings:**  Have a shaped inner race that helps keep the string centered, making tricks easier to land.\n*   **Response System:** This is what provides the friction needed to return the yoyo to your hand.\n    *   **Silicone Pads:** The most common type of response system. They provide good grip and are relatively easy to replace.\n    *   **O-Rings:** Less common, but can offer a different feel.\n\n**Recommendation:** A yoyo with a Size C stainless steel bearing and silicone pads is a good starting point.\n\n**6. Brand & Price:**\n\n*   **Reliable Brands:** Look into reputable brands like MagicYoyo, YoYoFactory, YoYoJam, Duncan, C3yoyodesign, iYoYo, TopYo, and R-Yo.\n*   **Price Range:** Unresponsive yoyos can range from $20 to $200+.  For beginners, a good quality aluminum yoyo in the $20-$50 range is a great place to start.\n\n**Recommendation:**  Start with a well-regarded model from a reputable brand within your budget. Don't overspend initially.\n\n**7. Research and Reviews:**\n\n*   **Read Reviews:** Look for reviews on yoyo websites, forums (like Reddit's r/throwers), and YouTube. See what other players are saying about different models.\n*   **Watch Videos:**  YouTube is a great resource for seeing how different yoyos perform in action.\n\n**8. Skill Level:**\n\n*   **Beginner (New to Unresponsive):** Focus on stability, ease of use, and durability.\n*   **Intermediate/Advanced:**  Consider factors like speed, agility, and specific trick styles.\n\n**Specific Recommendations for Beginners (Unresponsive):**\n\n*   **MagicYoyo N12 Shark Honor:** A popular and very affordable all-metal yoyo. Great value.\n*   **MagicYoyo V3:** Another excellent and affordable all-metal option.\n*   **Recess First Base:** Designed for learning; comes with both responsive and unresponsive bearings.\n*   **YoYoFactory Arrow (with included unresponsive bearing):** A great stepping stone to unresponsive.\n\n**General Tips for Beginners:**\n\n*   **Learn to Bind:** Binding is essential for returning an unresponsive yoyo. Watch plenty of tutorials and practice consistently.\n*   **Use Proper String:** Use yoyo string designed for unresponsive play.\n*   **Adjust String Length:** Experiment with string length to find what's comfortable for you.\n*   **Maintenance:** Keep your yoyo clean and lubricate the bearing if necessary (only use *very* small amounts of yoyo specific lubricant).\n*   **Start Simple:** Don't try to learn complex tricks right away. Focus on basic binds, mounts, and string tricks.\n*   **Be Patient:** Learning unresponsive yoyo takes time and practice. Don't get discouraged if you don't master it right away.\n\nBy considering these factors, you can choose an unresponsive yoyo that's well-suited to your skill level and preferences. Good luck, and have fun!\n",
